name: Robin Monks
tweet: In late-night summary: 5G is only good if it makes companies fix their infrastructure, and then LTE will get better too. Don‚Äôt let your telco convince you to pay more for their over-hyped new toy.

name: Robin Monks
tweet: Some of the misleading statements I‚Äôve seen: - 5G will allow real-time navigation (even 3G can do that) - 5G will power hospital surgeries (no, hospitals use fibre internet) - 5G will allow super-fast rural internet for homes (no, the signal doesn‚Äôt carry well enough for that)

name: Robin Monks
tweet: 5G mmwave basically requires hyper dense small tower deployments, and even then it will struggle to pass through walls into buildings. The technology just‚Ä¶ doesn‚Äôt make sense in practice. 5G is a lot of hype, and a lot of misleading marketing.

name: Robin Monks
tweet: Current LTE is fast enough to stream 4K video to your phone. It can handle two-way HD video chat, it supports IPv6 for better device identification. It‚Äôs also low-latency. 5G is a bit of an odd-duck. It‚Äôs fastest with millimetre wave transmission but that can‚Äôt travel far.

name: Robin Monks
tweet: The issue with current LTE implementations isn‚Äôt the technology, it‚Äôs shoddy network management, throttling and congestion. All of that won‚Äôt be fixed by changing the transmitters to 5G. It‚Äôs caused by companies not investing in their networks and trying to extract max profit.

name: Robin Monks
tweet: 5G is not going to make a difference in your life. All the marketing and campaigns around 5G are horrible hype. Nothing you do on your phone is going to be different with 5G, and don‚Äôt let companies try and convince you otherwise.
